content:
Be Aware of Base Lightning Component Internal DOM Structure Changes for Future Native Shadow Support

Salesforce is preparing base Lightning components to adopt native shadow DOM, enhancing performance and web standards compliance. This change affects internal DOM structure. Ensure tests don't rely on previous internal structure.

Where: This applies to Lightning Experience and all mobile app versions in all editions.

Why: Salesforce continuously aligns base Lightning components with web standards, announced in the Spring '23 release notes.

Adapted components include:

lightning-button
lightning-file-upload
lightning-formatted-name
lightning-formatted-number
lightning-navigation
lightning-progress-bar
lightning-progress-ring
lightning-select
lightning-textarea

Internal component structure is protected, but Salesforce may redesign it to improve performance, functionality, and accessibility.

IMPORTANT: If tests rely on the protected internal DOM structure, rewrite them as soon as possible.

How:

Review integration tests and selenium-based tests. Use UI Test Automation Model (UTAM) for supported integration tests, UTAM Page Objects, and Webdriver for Selenium-based tests. For CSS styling, follow Lightning Design System best practices in the Lightning Web Components Developer Guide.
title: Prepare for Base Lightning Component Changes
